more drugs are approved in the same setting. And then finally, some next steps.

81
00:04:59.530 --> 00:05:01.620
So there's the guy that started it. This is Clive Taylor.

82
00:05:02.180 --> 00:05:05.960
And the story goes that he wanted to look at a particular

83
00:05:05.980 --> 00:05:09.840
protein on a tissue slide, and so he did what we now call

84
00:05:09.860 --> 00:05:13.820
immunofluorescence. And he brought it over to his mentor, and his mentor said,

85
00:05:13.870 --> 00:05:16.460
"Yeah, Clive, this is great, but I can't see the surrounding tissue.

86
00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:20.660
I need the context." So Clive went back and learned how to

87
00:05:20.700 --> 00:05:24.610
use chromagens and began what we now know as immunohistochemistry, which is

88
00:05:24.620 --> 00:05:28.080
chromagenic. And in fact, this was back in 1974 that this

89
00:05:28.640 --> 00:05:31.940
occurred, and you can see that's sort of the timeline of changes in

90
00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:33.400
immunohistochemistry since then.

91
00:05:33.900 --> 00:05:37.440
Heat-induced antigen retrieval, polymer-based amplification, et cetera.

92
00:05:39.840 --> 00:05:41.100
And this is what it was designed for.

93
00:05:41.130 --> 00:05:44.940
It was designed for telling whether something is or is not expressing a protein,

94
00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:48.560
not on a binary level. So if it's p63 positive,

95
00:05:48.920 --> 00:05:51.420
it's a squamous cell carcinoma and TTF-1 negative.

96
00:05:51.820 --> 00:05:55.700
If it's TTF-1 positive, then it's an adenocarcinoma, and it helps to

97
00:05:55.760 --> 00:05:59.610
see all some synapsin staining. And if it's chromogranin positive,

98
00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:02.720
then you can call it a small cell, but these are chromogranin negative.

99
00:06:03.100 --> 00:06:06.830
And that's what IHC was designed for, and in fact, has been used for

100
00:06:07.100 --> 00:06:10.960
pretty much. But then what happened is that we decided that we would use it in a

101
00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:14.760
continuous basis and try to use it to score or assess levels.

102
00:06:15.170 --> 00:06:18.880
And so this was the original score, zero, one, two, three, and

103
00:06:18.920 --> 00:06:22.620
then to many more. This shows you two

104
00:06:22.660 --> 00:06:26.220
things, that you can still see that binary event between positive and

105
00:06:26.660 --> 00:06:28.100
not too positive or negative.

106
00:06:29.300 --> 00:06:32.260
But then what happened is we tried to splice this

107
00:06:32.340 --> 00:06:36.172
or-Stagger this and make this way more granular

108
00:06:36.212 --> 00:06:39.132
than the technology is capable of with the new

109
00:06:39.212 --> 00:06:42.872
anti-HER2 ADCs, where we had to separate zero from one.

110
00:06:43.472 --> 00:06:44.072
Can we do that?

111
00:06:45.332 --> 00:06:49.132
Well, here's the ASCO/CAP guidelines for how we're supposed to

112
00:06:49.152 --> 00:06:52.932
score. And the ASCO/CAP, in their wisdom, called both zero and one

113
00:06:53.012 --> 00:06:56.732
negative, because the assay was tell the positives from the negatives, and there

114
00:06:56.752 --> 00:07:00.692
was even a special trick called fish for the equivocales that you

115
00:07:00.732 --> 00:07:04.372
could use to mediate. But there's no trick to get zeros from

116
00:07:04.452 --> 00:07:07.952
ones. And in fact, the ASCO/CAP and the

117
00:07:08.172 --> 00:07:11.572
leaders of that organization didn't think that we could tell those apart.

118
00:07:11.652 --> 00:07:15.371
But now we have to, as zeros get no ADC

119
00:07:15.452 --> 00:07:18.232
and one plus gets trastuzumab drugs Tecan.

120
00:07:19.672 --> 00:07:23.282
So can you tell them apart? This is from the guidelines that they give to

121
00:07:23.292 --> 00:07:25.492
pathologists to learn how to do this.

122
00:07:25.532 --> 00:07:26.092
And this is

123
00:07:27.092 --> 00:07:31.012
from Pathway, a Roche Ventana pathway, anti-HER2 antibody

124
00:07:31.232 --> 00:07:34.092
4B5 that I'm going to show a little bit later as well.

125
00:07:34.552 --> 00:07:36.532
And this is an IHC, either one or zero.

126
00:07:37.322 --> 00:07:41.052
And here's the other one, either a one or zero. I'll go back and forth a few times.

127
00:07:41.092 --> 00:07:43.172
This is a one or zero. This is a one or zero.

128
00:07:43.232 --> 00:07:46.212
Now, I realize there might not be a lot of pathologists in the audience, but even

129
00:07:46.252 --> 00:07:46.752
if there were,

130
00:07:48.672 --> 00:07:51.752
I think that this is impossible. I can't tell them apart, and I can't tell them

131
00:07:51.792 --> 00:07:53.752
apart with any kind of reproducibility.

132
00:07:53.812 --> 00:07:57.182
So we asked the question, can real pathologists in the real world tell them apart?

133
00:07:57.732 --> 00:08:01.502
So we took 118 pathologists from multiple institutions around the country,

134
00:08:02.012 --> 00:08:02.122
all

135
00:08:03.752 --> 00:08:06.532
sign-out pathologists, that is, people in clinical practice.

136
00:08:06.922 --> 00:08:10.192
And we showed them 170 cases of breast cancer stained with

137
00:08:10.272 --> 00:08:12.032
IHC for HER2.

138
00:08:13.032 --> 00:08:16.742
You can see if you're pathologist number one, 45 or 45% of the

139
00:08:16.812 --> 00:08:18.712
patients don't qualify for T-DXd.

140
00:08:19.152 --> 00:08:22.772
But if you're pathologist number 18, only 15% of the patients don't qualify.

141
00:08:23.272 --> 00:08:26.692
So the patient gets drugged on the basis of their pathologist.

142
00:08:27.162 --> 00:08:29.912
I don't think that should happen. I think it should be on the basis of their tumor.

143
00:08:30.412 --> 00:08:33.712
And overall, we found a concordance of only around 29% or

144
00:08:33.913 --> 00:08:37.192
30% if you looked at just zero versus one.

145
00:08:38.072 --> 00:08:41.312
So it's not just us. A study in Japan was done with

146
00:08:41.393 --> 00:08:44.752
144 pathologists on 20 cases. Their overall agreement was

147
00:08:44.952 --> 00:08:48.932
63%. A study was done in Australia, nine pathologists with 60

148
00:08:49.032 --> 00:08:51.152
cases. Their overall agreement was 80%.

149
00:08:51.952 --> 00:08:55.832
And the best study done by 77 pathologists in Europe, led by

150
00:08:55.872 --> 00:08:59.852
Joe Rusoff and Beppe Viale, showed that for the zeros and

151
00:08:59.932 --> 00:09:03.732
ones, they could get around 82% concordance or 81%

152
00:09:03.772 --> 00:09:07.072
concordance. And they could train.

153
00:09:07.112 --> 00:09:09.621
They said, "Oh, we'll just need to train the pathologists how to do this." Well,

154
00:09:09.692 --> 00:09:13.612
training doesn't work. You can't train a pathologist to do this any more than

155
00:09:13.652 --> 00:09:17.592
you can train me to fly when I jump off the stage. It's not humanly possible.

156
00:09:17.742 --> 00:09:20.461
And that's what they showed here, that there was no difference before and after

157
00:09:20.492 --> 00:09:23.472
training. No significant difference before and after training.

158
00:09:23.512 --> 00:09:27.082
You'll note one thing, that for the positives, we're really good at that.

159
00:09:27.442 --> 00:09:29.152
That's what the assay was designed for.

160
00:09:29.252 --> 00:09:32.832
So we can tell the threes from the not threes, but we're not so good at telling the

161
00:09:32.852 --> 00:09:35.992
zeros from the ones. So is 80% good enough?

162
00:09:36.012 --> 00:09:39.872
Well, if I'm the patient, it's not. How do we do with biomarkers in other spaces?

163
00:09:39.912 --> 00:09:42.552
So this is EGFR mutation in lung cancer.

164
00:09:42.612 --> 00:09:46.532
This was done by 10 different groups 10 times and repeated

165
00:09:47.452 --> 00:09:49.852
with different operators, different instruments, and different days.

166
00:09:50.352 --> 00:09:54.181
And the average agreement is 99%. That's what patients

167
00:09:54.252 --> 00:09:55.412
deserve. And so we need to

168
00:09:56.292 --> 00:09:58.532
up our game a little bit, level up, as our kids say,

169
00:09:59.772 --> 00:10:02.832
to get to the point where we can have at least an agreement of

170
00:10:03.012 --> 00:10:05.121
95%, if not 99%.

171
00:10:06.552 --> 00:10:09.332
So just a little nomenclature. I'm going to talk about reading.

172
00:10:09.432 --> 00:10:12.621
That's what pathologists do. It's the subjective but expert interpretation of

173
00:10:12.672 --> 00:10:16.432
information on a histology slide and measurement, the quantitative

174
00:10:16.492 --> 00:10:19.872
objective determination of amounts or concentrations on a

175
00:10:19.892 --> 00:10:21.132
histopathology slide.

176
00:10:22.112 --> 00:10:25.692
How do we do that? Well, reading we talked about. That's the pathologist's opinion.

177
00:10:25.732 --> 00:10:29.562
And you saw that that can pretty much be around the 80 percentile for this

178
00:10:29.572 --> 00:10:33.102
particular question. For other questions, like how much immune cells there

179
00:10:33.172 --> 00:10:37.052
are in lung cancer in immunotherapy

180
00:10:37.112 --> 00:10:40.681
candidate patients, the agreement is closer to 50%.

181
00:10:40.892 --> 00:10:44.652
So reading is not a great way to assess protein

182
00:10:44.692 --> 00:10:48.432
concentration on slides. One way we could do it is circle the region of interest

183
00:10:48.442 --> 00:10:52.032
and just look at the intensity of the chromagen. And that's actually been done.

184
00:10:52.052 --> 00:10:55.832
But the chromagens are not linear and they're almost binary and they're not

185
00:10:55.852 --> 00:10:57.682
reproducible, and we'll talk about that in a minute.

186
00:10:58.102 --> 00:10:59.912
And the other way is to phenotype and count.

187
00:11:00.012 --> 00:11:03.932
So you can segment, find the cells with human intervention, teach software to find

188
00:11:03.972 --> 00:11:06.212
the cells, and then count the cells that are positive.

189
00:11:06.612 --> 00:11:10.302
But again, you're using a positive-negative threshold, which is binary, and that's

190
00:11:10.332 --> 00:11:13.542
not how biology works. Biology is a continuous platform,

191
00:11:13.632 --> 00:11:17.492
continuous expression of various proteins and other

192
00:11:17.512 --> 00:11:21.342
biomolecules. And so the best way, in my opinion, to do it is measurement, and

193
00:11:21.372 --> 00:11:23.792
measurement is intensity divided by area.

194
00:11:23.852 --> 00:11:27.512
So to illustrate this, this is a made-up slide of a patient with

195
00:11:27.522 --> 00:11:29.612
various cells at various gray intensities.

196
00:11:30.132 --> 00:11:34.052
If your cutoff is zero gray intensity, then you only have three of those.

197
00:11:34.072 --> 00:11:37.502
But if your cutoff is 15, then you'd have 50% positive.

198
00:11:37.572 --> 00:11:40.992
But if your cutoff is 35%, you'd have 30% positive.

199
00:11:41.092 --> 00:11:44.832
So this isn't a great way to score. We built a

200
00:11:45.252 --> 00:11:48.952
semi-continuous scoring system called the H-score, which is a

201
00:11:48.992 --> 00:11:51.922
continuous method for analysis of IHC, where you have the

202
00:11:54.272 --> 00:11:57.552
ordinal score times the percentage of cells that show that ordinal score.

203
00:11:57.592 --> 00:12:01.172
This is from McCarty in 1994. But the problem is that if the

204
00:12:01.192 --> 00:12:04.332
intensity is a little different or the judgment is a little different, you'll be

205
00:12:04.412 --> 00:12:07.872
off by a factor of two or three or even more.

206
00:12:07.892 --> 00:12:11.232
And this is actually a proof of that. This is a paper from David Dobbs et al.

207
00:12:11.292 --> 00:12:14.872
that just was published in "Lancet." And each one of these dots represents a

208
00:12:14.952 --> 00:12:16.832
different CLIA lab, mostly in Europe.

209
00:12:17.412 --> 00:12:20.982
And so if you're this lab, your lower limit of detection is about

210
00:12:21.112 --> 00:12:21.712
30,000

211
00:12:23.532 --> 00:12:27.352
molecules per cell. But if you're this lab, you can't detect anything less than

212
00:12:27.552 --> 00:12:31.372
90,000. So these are all CLIA labs that are certified labs,

213
00:12:31.752 --> 00:12:35.592
and they're all using the test exactly according to the label, the FDA protocol

214
00:12:35.652 --> 00:12:39.462
for this. And they're still variable over a scale of almost a half an

215
00:12:39.652 --> 00:12:42.321
order of magnitude or more than that, three times.

216
00:12:42.742 --> 00:12:46.282
And so this is why I don't think chromagen should be used for quantification, is

217
00:12:46.312 --> 00:12:50.284
that we're just not reproducible for chromagens.So what we

218
00:12:50.324 --> 00:12:53.664
can do is we can make a quantitative assay, but we're going to have to jump to

219
00:12:53.704 --> 00:12:55.624
fluorescence. So how do we do that?

220
00:12:55.664 --> 00:12:59.424
Well, this is a summary slide of all the things.

221
00:12:59.444 --> 00:13:02.904
We start with a cell line array. These are all cell lines that have had the amount

222
00:13:02.944 --> 00:13:06.444
of protein determined by mass spec, and then the area determined.

223
00:13:06.484 --> 00:13:06.664
So the

224
00:13:08.144 --> 00:13:12.084
mass spec gives us attomoles per microgram, and then we can convert

225
00:13:12.144 --> 00:13:15.784
that to attomoles per square millimeter by assessing the area of each

226
00:13:15.824 --> 00:13:19.744
cell and then putting that together into a standard curve, just like

227
00:13:19.824 --> 00:13:23.584
college biochemistry. And we can have the attomoles per millimeter on this

228
00:13:23.624 --> 00:13:27.484
side and then the signal on this side. How do we get the signal?

229
00:13:27.524 --> 00:13:31.284
Well, we do quantitative fluorescence, just like immunohistochemistry, but with

230
00:13:31.324 --> 00:13:33.964
fluorophores and tyramide signal amplification.

231
00:13:34.404 --> 00:13:37.974
So we can look at the fluorescent signal only within the cytokeratin-positive

232
00:13:38.044 --> 00:13:41.944
pixels. Cytokeratin-positive pixels gives us the area, and the sum of

233
00:13:41.984 --> 00:13:45.934
the intensity is our average Q score, which can then be converted to an attomoles

234
00:13:45.984 --> 00:13:49.644
per square millimeter. It turns out we can't just directly compare the

235
00:13:49.724 --> 00:13:53.624
attomoles because different biologic targets have different levels.

236
00:13:53.684 --> 00:13:57.164
So what we propose to do is compare the percentiles in a

237
00:13:57.204 --> 00:14:00.664
population. And this is the work of Jack Robinson in my lab, and

238
00:14:00.964 --> 00:14:01.284
others.

239
00:14:02.704 --> 00:14:04.304
Here's how it works in the actual CLIA lab.

240
00:14:04.344 --> 00:14:07.724
We have a CLIA lab called Quantitative Diagnostics and Anatomic Pathology.

241
00:14:08.184 --> 00:14:11.864
So you can send us your slide, and we'll batch stain it with up to nine

242
00:14:11.964 --> 00:14:15.564
slides per tray. There's 10 slide tray holders in the Leica bond,

243
00:14:16.004 --> 00:14:18.404
and one of those slides is going to be that cell line control.

244
00:14:18.484 --> 00:14:20.824
So one cell line control for every tray.

245
00:14:20.864 --> 00:14:24.824
Maybe someday we'll put one on every slide, but right now one per 10 is about where

246
00:14:24.844 --> 00:14:28.174
we're working. The biopsies scanned in attomoles per square millimeter are

247
00:14:28.204 --> 00:14:31.664
calculated in the background. Then a critical piece happens.

248
00:14:31.694 --> 00:14:33.644
The pathologist circles the critical part.

249
00:14:33.724 --> 00:14:37.704
But the pathologist doesn't usually read fluorescence, so we've computationally

250
00:14:37.744 --> 00:14:41.304
converted the fluorescent image into something that looks like a conventional

251
00:14:41.324 --> 00:14:44.004
DAB-based or chromogen-based IHC.

252
00:14:44.424 --> 00:14:47.834
And then the pathologist can circle the region of interest, thereby not measuring

253
00:14:48.584 --> 00:14:51.764
normal ducts or stroma that has no epithelium in it and

254
00:14:52.324 --> 00:14:55.764
leading to a more accurate measurement, and also giving the pathologist confidence

255
00:14:55.804 --> 00:14:58.404
that what they're measuring is actually what they're supposed to be measuring, that

256
00:14:58.464 --> 00:15:02.004
is, the malignant tumor. You can see the weakness of this technology is

257
00:15:02.044 --> 00:15:05.784
illustrated here. The level of HER2 in this region of the

258
00:15:05.844 --> 00:15:09.244
slide is different than the risk level in this region of the slide, and that's

259
00:15:09.284 --> 00:15:12.184
inherent heterogeneity. And we haven't figured that out yet.

260
00:15:12.204 --> 00:15:13.964
We're working on it, but we haven't figured that out yet.

261
00:15:14.044 --> 00:15:16.884
So for now, we just average across the entire section.

262
00:15:18.264 --> 00:15:19.984
When you do that, you get a result like this.

263
00:15:20.064 --> 00:15:23.964
This is 316 core biopsies from breast cancer patients actually seen

264
00:15:24.024 --> 00:15:27.424
in our clinic between 2022 and 2023.

265
00:15:27.904 --> 00:15:31.544
And this was the IHC score that resulted in them getting trastuzumab or not and

266
00:15:31.564 --> 00:15:34.724
getting them categorized by what type of therapy they would get.

267
00:15:35.104 --> 00:15:36.044
And you can see the three

268
00:15:36.884 --> 00:15:40.784
pluses and two plus amplifies, the reds and oranges are all pretty much on the top.

269
00:15:40.824 --> 00:15:43.444
We're good at that. But we're not so good at the lows.

270
00:15:43.464 --> 00:15:46.684
The zeroes are green, and the one pluses are blue.

271
00:15:47.064 --> 00:15:50.724
And you can see that they're essentially interchangeable on the bottom level of the

272
00:15:50.733 --> 00:15:54.624
scale. This is actually now published, and I'll show you the

273
00:15:54.644 --> 00:15:58.404
publication in a minute. But if you do two at once, you can see an

274
00:15:58.464 --> 00:16:01.673
interesting thing, an almost inverse relationship between

275
00:16:01.704 --> 00:16:05.644
Trop-2 and HER2. And so the patients with low Trop-2

276
00:16:05.654 --> 00:16:09.524
are down here, but they have high HER2, and then there's patients

277
00:16:09.564 --> 00:16:12.784
with high Trop-2 and low HER2 down over here.

278
00:16:14.424 --> 00:16:18.344
How accurate is the assay? Well, it's a CLIA lab assay, and it's an analytic assay,

279
00:16:18.804 --> 00:16:22.534
so we can actually calculate the LOD and the LOQ, limit of detection and limit of

280
00:16:22.584 --> 00:16:26.114
quantification. And we can calculate the CV, both inter-assay,

281
00:16:26.504 --> 00:16:30.364
three days with a minimum of a week washout, three different days, or intra-assay

282
00:16:30.404 --> 00:16:33.964
with different operators and different trays of the Leica bond, and they're all

283
00:16:33.984 --> 00:16:37.934
below 10%. So this assay is now New

284
00:16:37.944 --> 00:16:41.654
York State Department of Health approved and approved in our CLIA lab at Yale, and

285
00:16:41.684 --> 00:16:45.624
we're working on licensing the assay so it can be used more broadly than just in

286
00:16:45.664 --> 00:16:46.964
my little QDAT lab.

287
00:16:48.564 --> 00:16:52.124
This is the publication of the prospective assessment that was published in

288
00:16:52.164 --> 00:16:54.904
"Laboratory Investigation." And this is how the assay is built.

289
00:16:54.944 --> 00:16:58.684
It's now open source, and all the software associated with it is open

290
00:16:58.744 --> 00:17:00.064
source downloadable on GitHub.

291
00:17:01.844 --> 00:17:05.825
So the next step is selective markers, and I think selective markers are really the

292
00:17:05.904 --> 00:17:09.884
strength of measurement. Because ultimately, we know that there's

293
00:17:09.924 --> 00:17:12.264
a diagnostic biomarker. I showed you that in the beginning.

294
00:17:12.325 --> 00:17:13.624
That's what Clive Taylor invented.

295
00:17:14.024 --> 00:17:16.864
Then there's prognostic biomarkers, and there aren't many of those.

296
00:17:16.904 --> 00:17:17.004
But

297
00:17:18.045 --> 00:17:21.904
perhaps the best example is Oncotype. That can tell you who does not need drug.

298
00:17:21.964 --> 00:17:25.144
So prognostic markers say that the standard of care is good enough.

299
00:17:25.164 --> 00:17:27.704
And so we won't see those from pharma companies anytime soon.

300
00:17:28.164 --> 00:17:31.024
But the predictive markers are what the pharma companies have brought to us.

301
00:17:31.404 --> 00:17:34.684
And each one, the clinical trial, a predictive marker is a companion

302
00:17:34.744 --> 00:17:37.384
diagnostic. But I think what we need is beyond that.

303
00:17:37.434 --> 00:17:39.844
I would argue that we need a selective biomarker now.

304
00:17:40.284 --> 00:17:42.344
In fact, selective biomarkers have been around.

305
00:17:42.404 --> 00:17:44.424
That's when you do a 400-gene panel.

306
00:17:44.904 --> 00:17:48.484
You're selecting which gene mutation is present and which drug you should give on

307
00:17:48.504 --> 00:17:52.034
the basis of that mutation. I believe it's time to move that to protein,

308
00:17:52.484 --> 00:17:56.404
but it's harder in protein because you have to measure it with a low CV.

309
00:17:57.814 --> 00:18:01.804
So there's about 260 known antigens being clinically tested, and when I

310
00:18:01.824 --> 00:18:05.454
presented this a couple of days ago, someone told me, "No, there's 400." So there's

311
00:18:05.504 --> 00:18:09.004
a lot either way. There's a lot of ADCs in clinical trials, which mean

312
00:18:09.344 --> 00:18:13.104
soon there will be multiple targets for the same clinical setting.

313
00:18:13.144 --> 00:18:15.744
In fact, there already is in advanced breast cancer.

314
00:18:15.784 --> 00:18:18.904
You can get either a cetuximab govitecan or trastuzumab

315
00:18:18.924 --> 00:18:21.844
deruxtecan in advanced second-line setting.

316
00:18:22.604 --> 00:18:24.144
So how do you know which one to give first?

317
00:18:24.184 --> 00:18:26.064
Well, I would argue this is what you should do.

318
00:18:26.104 --> 00:18:29.964
You should measure in attomoles per square millimeter, both HER2 and

319
00:18:30.004 --> 00:18:33.294
Trop-2, then proportion them in the population.

320
00:18:33.344 --> 00:18:37.164
And this patient would get T-DXd first because they are relatively low

321
00:18:37.224 --> 00:18:38.824
Trop-2 and much higher

322
00:18:39.804 --> 00:18:42.964
HER2, even though the actual attomoles per square millimeter aren't that much

323
00:18:43.004 --> 00:18:43.364
different.

324
00:18:44.784 --> 00:18:47.704
This is what the plot looks like and the inverse relationship that I think is

325
00:18:47.744 --> 00:18:51.724
really important that will be generalizable, and I'll show more of this later

326
00:18:51.784 --> 00:18:54.764
on in the talk. But in each case, you standardize them.

327
00:18:54.864 --> 00:18:58.584
So you can have attomoles on each axis and then have each

328
00:18:58.644 --> 00:19:02.204
patient represent a dot and figure out where your patient is in the

329
00:19:02.684 --> 00:19:05.524
scatter plot in order to decide which drug to give

330
00:19:05.564 --> 00:19:09.548
first.So does it work? Well, we're still in

331
00:19:09.588 --> 00:19:12.728
the process of proving that. This is a preliminary retrospective study that we've

332
00:19:12.768 --> 00:19:15.647
done at Yale with 65 cases, which isn't very much.

333
00:19:16.048 --> 00:19:19.288
All received T-DXd in the second-line or higher setting, and they were

334
00:19:19.348 --> 00:19:23.188
all run by the Troplex assay to measure Trop-2 and HER2 on each

335
00:19:23.248 --> 00:19:27.148
case. And this is what we found, that most of the three pluses are up here, as

336
00:19:27.188 --> 00:19:30.868
you'd expect, but there's occasionally a fair number of two pluses down here in a

337
00:19:30.908 --> 00:19:33.358
relatively low range, and then the zeros and ones.

338
00:19:33.768 --> 00:19:37.088
Surprisingly, there's some zeros and ones even in the pretty high range, which we

339
00:19:37.108 --> 00:19:38.388
don't completely understand yet

340
00:19:39.607 --> 00:19:43.448
other than it might be that the IHC

341
00:19:43.508 --> 00:19:46.848
is not so good on really small pieces of tissue, which is what you have on a small

342
00:19:46.888 --> 00:19:48.728
biopsy in the metastatic setting.

343
00:19:50.168 --> 00:19:54.068
Well, here, with only 65, we just divided the population of HER2

344
00:19:54.128 --> 00:19:54.568
positive

345
00:19:55.388 --> 00:19:59.228
or HER2 animals per square millimeter at the median, and you can see

346
00:19:59.288 --> 00:20:03.128
that the high levels above the median has a 12.8-month median

347
00:20:03.528 --> 00:20:06.488
time to next treatment compared to the low levels, only a

348
00:20:06.528 --> 00:20:09.188
7.5-month time to next treatment.

349
00:20:11.308 --> 00:20:15.068
So we just finished and haven't analyzed the data yet, the rest of the

350
00:20:15.128 --> 00:20:18.668
cohort. Now we have 150 cases, and it looks almost

351
00:20:18.688 --> 00:20:22.548
exactly the same in terms of dividing by quartiles for overall

352
00:20:22.608 --> 00:20:25.828
survival and dividing by time to next treatment.

353
00:20:26.208 --> 00:20:29.928
That is that the highest level do the best and the lowest levels do the worst.

354
00:20:30.628 --> 00:20:34.428
But since we were using the Troplex assay, we could also

355
00:20:34.828 --> 00:20:38.688
look at Trop-2. And this is completely unexpected, and I'm not sure if I

356
00:20:38.708 --> 00:20:42.608
believe it myself or not yet, but if you have high Trop-2, you do poorly

357
00:20:42.668 --> 00:20:46.228
on T-DXd. I'm not sure why that is, but maybe there's some

358
00:20:46.288 --> 00:20:48.428
interaction between Trop-2 and HER2.

359
00:20:48.468 --> 00:20:51.288
But it emphasizes the importance of a selective biomarker.

360
00:20:51.708 --> 00:20:53.088
That is, if you know that you're going to

361
00:20:54.048 --> 00:20:57.528
give one or the other, you want your biomarker to reflect the biology of the

362
00:20:57.568 --> 00:21:01.238
patient's tumor. And if it's high Trop-2, probably is

363
00:21:01.368 --> 00:21:05.048
not only a good idea to give trastuzumab deruxtecan but a bad

364
00:21:05.128 --> 00:21:05.888
idea

365
00:21:07.368 --> 00:21:11.108
because if it's high Trop-2, they won't respond to trastuzumab deruxtecan.

366
00:21:12.428 --> 00:21:16.387
This also bore out in the 150 cases where patients that have the

367
00:21:16.448 --> 00:21:19.528
highest level of Trop-2 do really quite poorly

368
00:21:20.128 --> 00:21:23.088
on

369
00:21:23.108 --> 00:21:26.308
T-DXd. And this is a similar pattern on time to treatment.

370
00:21:26.628 --> 00:21:29.928
Data still to be completed, but just as a glimpse.

371
00:21:31.508 --> 00:21:35.428
So in the prospective study, 6% of the cases have levels of

372
00:21:35.448 --> 00:21:39.148
HER2 that are below the LOD. Those are the true negatives,

373
00:21:39.528 --> 00:21:42.808
and there are patients out there that have no target for HER2.

374
00:21:43.108 --> 00:21:46.268
But not 40% or 20%, but closer to

375
00:21:46.448 --> 00:21:50.218
6% with an analytic assay. And so those are

376
00:21:50.228 --> 00:21:54.188
probably the true nulls. Seventy-one percent of the patients at Yale that were

377
00:21:54.228 --> 00:21:56.068
called IHC equals zero had

378
00:21:57.608 --> 00:22:00.328
analytic measures above the limit of quantification.

379
00:22:00.348 --> 00:22:03.568
That means there may be a fair number of patients out there that should be getting

380
00:22:03.608 --> 00:22:07.548
T-DXd that aren't because they have target present, but by IHC,

381
00:22:07.628 --> 00:22:10.128
we didn't think they did by a subjective test.

382
00:22:11.628 --> 00:22:14.688
The retrospective study showed a difference in median survival, and the

383
00:22:14.728 --> 00:22:18.588
retrospective study also showed a curious result where high Trop-2 are less

384
00:22:18.648 --> 00:22:20.508
likely to benefit from T-DXd.

385
00:22:22.388 --> 00:22:25.388
So the last thing in the last minute or so, I want to talk about next steps.

386
00:22:25.848 --> 00:22:28.927
And the next steps are illustrated in this work that is coming out today.

387
00:22:28.988 --> 00:22:32.288
That's what the QR code is about looking at HER3, another

388
00:22:33.488 --> 00:22:35.308
ADC target for the drug pertuzumab.

